<DOCNO> AP891004-0001 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the captain of the uss iowa and three 
subordinates were charged with dereliction of duty for violating 
administrative procedures aboard the battleship on which 47 men 
were killed in an explosion the navy said wednesday 
the actions against the four men ranging from administrative 
corrective measures to punitive letters of admonition resulted 
from admirals mast hearings conducted earlier this week on board 
the iowa in the mediterranean by vice adm joseph s donnell iii 
none of the men was relieved of his duties 
each person was charged with a dereliction of duty under the 
uniform code of military justice as a result of administrative 
deficiencies found in the uss iowa investigation the navy said 
despite violations of procedure the navy said none of the 
discrepancies resulted in or contributed to the explosion on 
april 19 
a navy investigation concluded that gunners mate clayton 
hartwig most likely caused the explosion in the battleships 
no 2 gun turret by inserting a detonator between two powder bags 
the report which has come under congressional scrutiny turned 
up numerous lax procedures including experimentation with 
extrastrength gunpower and projectile loads the navy said those 
allegations prompted the admirals mast hearings 
as a result of the hearings capt fred p moosally commander 
of the battleship and the only man publicly identified by the 
service and his operations officer cmdr robert finney were 
subject to administrative corrective measures the navy said 
navy sources identified finney and the other two men cited in 
hearings 
a navy source speaking on condition of anonymity said moosally 
and finney will not have letters that affect their potential 
promotions placed in their files although they will be given the 
letters 
however the source said their annual fitness reports will 
reflect the problems on the iowa and their careers are likely to be 
damaged 
stiffer disciplinary action was given to the weapons officer and 
the fire control gunner who were given punitive letters of 
admonition the weapons officer was fined 2000 and the gunner 
1000 but the fines were forgiven 
the weapons control officer has been identified as cmdr robert 
j kissinger while the gunner was master chief petty officer 
stephen skelly 
the service said the action against moosally was less severe 
because subordinates were held accountable for deficiencies in 
their specifically assigned duties 
kathy kubicina of cleveland hartwigs sister said she was not 
surprised by the navy action 
they got merely a slap on the wrists if they would have 
gotten something harsher the navy would have had to admit their 
own guilt i was prepared for this which is absolutely nothing 
she said 
donnell based his punishment on what he concluded was 
appropriate for each person the navy said insisting that the 
administrative deficiencies had nothing to do with the explosion 
it should be stressed that although deficiencies in the iowas 
training documentation weapons handling requirements and adherence 
to safety procedures were found within the weapons department the 
investigation determined that these shortcomings did not cause or 
contribute to the explosion the navy said in a statement 
in deciding on the punishments donnell was required to 
separate the larger tragedy from the process of determining 
accountability for administrative training safety and 
ordnancehandling deficiencies the navy said 
all four men can appeal for a review of the actions 
</TEXT>
