<TEXT>
del wood the grand ole oprys ragtime 
pianist whose 1951 recording of down yonder sold more than 3 
million copies died tuesday at a nashville hospital following a 
stroke she was 69 
miss wood became a member of the opry in 1953 and was the only 
person regularly featured at the grand ole opry keyboard 
minnie pearl is the only woman who has been on the famous 
country music show longer than miss wood said opry spokesman 
gerald strobel 
miss wood suffered a stroke last week and was in intensive care 
at baptist hospital until her death tuesday night said pat harris 
a family friend 
known as the queen of the ivories her real name was 
adelaide hazelwood in an interview with the associated press in 
1984 she said she still practiced about three hours a week 
id never go on the opry without first doing a runthrough if 
i live to be 100 im going to do the best i can she said 
grand ole opry star roy acuff said miss wood was a fine pianist 
i dont know of any weve had on the opry better on the piano 
than she was she made a very fine reputation for herself in 
country music he said 
miss woods parents gave her a piano on her fifth birthday and 
she was schooled in classical music until ragtime a 
jazzinfluenced style of pop music became her passion as a 
teenager 
ragtime has so much getupandgo that its infectious its 
part of our heritage she said 
after graduating from high school in nashville she worked 
playing sheet music for customers at a dime store and as a payroll 
clerk for the state health department while pursuing her music 
career on weekends and at night 
she cut a record featuring mine all mine for rca and with 
down yonder on the flip side down yonder was second on the 
pop charts for 27 weeks and was also a country hit 
miss wood also played five songs in the movie rhinestone 
which starred dolly parton and sylvester stallone 
</TEXT>
