<TEXT>
the annual top performance awards of the 
associated press managing editors association have been presented 
to the aps beijing bureau national writer fred bayles science 
writer daniel q haney and ap photographers jeff widener of 
bangkok liu heung shing of seoul and scott applewhite of 
washington 
the organization also named boston newswoman leslie dreyfous 
winner of the ninth annual john l dougherty award for excellence 
by a young ap writer 
the top performance awards recognize outstanding work by ap 
reporters and photographers in the previous 12 months in two 
reporting categories writing on deadline and feature writing 
and two photography categories spot news and feature photography 
the winners were awarded 1500 and a plaque at the apme 
convention here tuesday 
the ap beijing bureau was honored for coverage of the 
suppression of the studentled democracy movement in china those 
specifically cited were jim abrams kathy wilhelm and john pomfret 
of beijing terril jones of tokyo and dan biers of hong kong jones 
and biers were on assignment in beijing 
bayles and haney both of the aps boston bureau were chosen 
for a threepart series six miles up and sleepy about the 
risks caused by fatigue among airline pilots 
widener and liu were selected cowinners for their photo 
coverage of the student demonstrations and subsequent government 
crackdown in beijing applewhite was singled out for a photo of 
president bush and lee atwater the republican national committee 
chairman mugging while accompanying a band during the presidential 
inauguration 
the john l dougherty award is named for a former apme leader 
and managing editor of the rochester ny newspapers who had an 
abiding interest in good writing and helped young writers improve 
their skills he died in 1980 ms dreyfous received a 1000 cash 
award and a plaque 
additional awards for excellence in the top performance 
reporting competition went to 
maureen johnson of london and earleen fisher and sharon 
herbaugh both of new delhi for coverage of the soviet troop 
withdrawal from afghanistan and its aftermath 
johnthor dahlburg andrew katell mark porubcansky all of 
moscow sydney rubin of paris and carol j williams of bonn for 
coverage of the catastrophic earthquake in soviet armenia 
nancy shulins ap newsfeatures for her story lost 
innocence about two elderly vermont brothers whose peaceful 
lives were shattered by a violent robbery 
ap latin america staff members kevin noblet monte hayes todd 
lewan peter mcfarren susana hayward harold olmos eduardo 
gallardo bruce handler and ed mccullough and lisa genasci of the 
new york foreign desk for their periodic series continent in 
crisis about the economic political and social turbulence in 
latin america 
david foster scott mccartney and tad bartimus all ap 
regional reporters and hal spencer of olympia wash for course 
of doom an examination of the years of errors that made the 
exxon valdez oilspill disaster inevitable 
awards for excellence in photography were given to 
boris yurchenko of moscow for his work in the aftermath of the 
armenian earthquake and for a photo of mikhail gorbachev checking 
his watch while margaret thatcher spoke in london in april 
katsumi kashahara of tokyo for a picture of greg louganis 
hitting his head on the diving board at the seoul olympics 
jack smith of portland ore for a closeup of an oilcovered 
bird after the alaska spill and for a photo of native alaskans 
tending to a gray whale trapped in the ice 
amy sancetta of philadelphia for her photo series documenting 
the progress of a young armenian boy undergoing surgery and therapy 
for injuries incurred in the armenian earthquake 
the apme comprises managing editors and other news executives of 
the 1478 member newspapers of the ap the worlds oldest and 
largest newsgathering organization 
</TEXT>
