<TEXT>
a leading hispanic group and the alcohol and 
tobacco industries are dismissing claims that beer cigarette and 
fastfood ads are jeopardizing latinos health 
the center for science in the public interest said in a 
publication called marketing disease to hispanics that latinos 
suffer from an increasing number of health problems related to 
drinking smoking and highfat fast foods 
the beer institute a trade association said tuesdays report 
had no scientific basis and rejected suggestions that the beer 
industry is promoting alcoholism among hispanics 
institute president james sanders said money contributed by the 
industry to the hispanic community benefits public health literacy 
and cultural programs as well as economic development 
problems of nutrition and substance abuse in the hispanic 
community are real and they deserve real action and real 
solutions sanders said taking down billboards and shuttering 
hamburger stands wont help these very real problems 
anheuserbusch spokesman jesse aguirre said his companys 
advertising promotes responsible beer drinking and discourages 
alcohol abuse he called the report irresponsible patronizing 
it assumes that hispanic american citizens cannot make sound 
educated consumer decisions just like other segments of the 
american public aguirre said 
walker merryman vice president of the tobacco institute a 
trade association for the cigarette industry agreed anybody who 
sees an advertisement for a product is capable of making a decision 
about whether to use it 
dr carlos molina a member of the centers board and president 
of the latino caucus of the american public health association 
said hispanic groups have been silent on the issue largely because 
they receive about 1 million a year from alcohol tobacco and 
junkfood companies 
that support muzzles our national leaders on vital health 
issues he said 
however the national council of la raza a leading nonprofit 
hispanic service organization with affiliates in 26 states 
rejected that conclusion susan herrera vice president of the 
council estimated the group gets 2 percent of its funding from 
beer or tobacco companies 
we dont feel compromised she said if we cant take 
peoples money and do what we need to do then we shouldnt have any 
business taking that money 
the council has been in the business of drug and alcohol abuse 
programs and were still operating them she said 
the report cites studies showing 
men of mexican heritage have a 40 percent higher risk of death 
due to cirrhosis of the liver than white men 
in colorado lung cancer rates among hispanic men increased 132 
percent between 1970 and 1980 compared with a 12 percent increase 
among white men in new mexico lung cancer deaths nearly tripled 
for hispanic men from 1958 to 1982 while doubling for white men 
obesity linked to adultonset diabetes among hispanic women 
over age 18 was about 25 percent more prevalent than among white 
women 
the report calls for higher excise taxes on alcoholic beverages 
and cigarettes a ban on cigarette vending machines and a ban on 
all alcoholic beverages and cigarette advertising that links those 
products with health and youthfulness 
the center for science in the public interest is a nonprofit 
organization that focuses on health and nutrition 
