<TEXT>
the newspaper industry faced with a 
decline in readership must develop customer obsession to 
reverse the slide the president of the associated press managing 
editors told the apme convention 
readership surveys can be useful but they arent enough 
said paul janensch editor and general manager of the rockland 
journalnews in new york citys suburban rockland county ny 
surveys cant halt sliding readership unless the editor and the 
editors staff are fanatical about getting close to the community 
opening the annual apme convention on tuesday janensch said 
steadily declining readership confronts us with the most serious 
problem facing newspapers today and that it even hits markets 
where the economy is booming 
if you are lucky enough to be in a growing market and your 
circulation is going up you may think you dont have a problem 
he said 
wrong even where circulation is going up net newspaper 
penetration is going down there are no exceptions 
in 1967 about 73 percent of us adults said they read a 
newspaper every day he said last year the number was down to 
51 percent 
call it what you will customer obsession putting the reader 
first serving the constituents we must do it better janensch 
said i firmly believe that if we build a strong rapport with our 
communities we will prosper if we dont we will fade away 
while many are captivated by national news and bigname events 
most of americas newspapers survive by providing residents of the 
community with information they need in their daily lives he said 
is your newspaper first and foremost a local newspaper 
asked janensch do you care as much about the expansion of a 
local business as you do about the national trade deficit 
in addition to building community ties janensch said a 
newspapers staff must reflect the papers market 
does your staff at all levels reflect the racial and ethnic 
diversity of your target readership he asked the editors are 
