<TEXT>
federal officials announced civil suits or 
fines today against 11 cities where local authorities allegedly 
allowed untreated toxic industrial wastes into public sewage 
systems 
the justice department lawsuits on behalf of the environmental 
protection agency were filed against nine cities including 
detroit phoenix and san antonio texas charging violations of 
federal water pollution laws 
in addition san antonio and two other cities agreed to pay 
fines totaling 349000 as part of separate consent agreements 
involving past violations that stemmed from the illegal discharges 
epa officials said 
the cases announced today involved lawsuits filed this week 
four of them today in federal courts in massachusetts michigan 
texas arizona new york and pennsylvania 
the new actions brought to 61 cities in 21 states against which 
either administrative penalties have been sought or civil suits 
were filed this year because of improper releases of toxic 
industrial wastes 
so far the cities have agreed to pay more than 21 million in 
fines the epa is seeking another 19 million in penalties in the 
two dozen cases that remain open a figure that could increase once 
proposed penalties are included from the latest round of lawsuits 
nearly twothirds of the 61 cases were initiated during the past 
two months in some cases the actions were taken by the states 
involved after violations surfaced during epa inspections of 
records officials said 
in the largest case the epa and denver reached a settlement in 
august in which city officials agreed to pay more than 11 million 
in penalties for alleged violations of clean water laws in 
connection with toxic discharges through the municipal sewage 
treatment plant 
these lawsuits and penalties are designed to send a 
message to city and county officials said epa administrator 
william reilly 
attorney general dick thornburgh said the lawsuits reflect the 
bush administrations determination not to sit idly by while our 
waters continue to be befouled 
we simply cannot allow harmful pollutants to reach our rivers 
and streams untreated local officials have a legal and moral 
responsibility to those they represent and to other users of our 
nations waterways to make sure local industries abide by the 
rules thornburgh said 
the federal lawsuits and epa administrative enforcement actions 
allege that the cities failed to adequately identify the industrial 
discharges allowed discharges in some cases without proper 
permits didnt screen samples of the wastewater to determine if 
industrial plants were in compliance and failed to take action 
against polluters violating the pretreatment requirements 
the epa said more than 870 million pounds of toxic industrial 
chemicals including cyanide arsenic and hazardous heavy metals 
such as cadmium and lead were dumped into public sewage treatment 
plants in 1987 the latest year for which figures are available 
these wastes combine with normal sewage and after treatment are 
released into open waters but the treatment for normal sewage 
isnt enough for the toxic wastes so federal law requires that if 
such chemical wastes are to be released through the sewage system 
they must first undergo pretreatment at the industrial plant 
but according to epa estimates as many as onethird of the 
1500 municipal sewage treatment facilities dont adequately 
monitor such pretreatment or take action against violators to 
ensure that the toxic wastes undergo treatment before entering the 
sewage system 
civil lawsuits were filed this week against gloucester mass 
dunkirk ny easton and punxsutawney pa detroit beaumont el 
paso and san antonio texas and phoenix ariz 
the epa said consent agreements for past violations also were 
reached this week with nacogdoches texas 60000 fine 
bellefonte pa 64000 fine and san antonio 225000 fine 
