<TEXT>
a skeptical supreme court was urged today to 
overturn a dallas ordinance that imposes strict licensing 
requirements for sexually oriented businesses 
john h weston a beverly hills calif lawyer representing the 
businesses said the texas citys ordinance imposes a prior 
restraint on free speech that violates the constitution 
under the ordinance one may not disseminate speech one has 
chosen to disseminate absent a permit weston said the local law 
permits the city to do indirectly what it can not do directly 
he said 
were not dealing with nuclear power plants weston added in 
arguing there is no lawful ground for such strict rules 
but the justices repeatedly challenged westons assertions 
chief justice william h rehnquist addressing one of the 
lawyers main arguments said there is no precedent for giving 
special consideration to bookstores seeking licenses to do business 
there is no supreme court case close to suggesting that 
rehnquist said 
justice antonin scalia in frequently barbed questioning said 
to weston you mean that every bookstore cannot be subject to 
normal business licensing 
dallas city attorney analeslie muncy said the ordinance is a 
vital weapon against crime and urban decay 
the licensing rules are aimed at businesses that are 100 
percent sexually oriented she said 
she added that nothing prevents the business owners from 
distributing their wares in other ways 
they can sell the same material through the mails door to 
door or on a street corner she said 
the justices are expected to announce a ruling by july 
providing new guidelines on how far communities may go to limit 
sexually oriented businesses 
the dallas ordinance is being challenged by owners of adult 
bookstores motion picture theaters nightclubs and motels 
the law also applies to nudemodel studios and sexualencounter 
establishments but no such businesses were represented in todays 
case 
the 1986 ordinance requires sexually oriented businesses to 
obtain a license issued by the city police chief 
such businesses must permit inspection of their premises during 
operating hours no one convicted of a variety crimes including 
promoting prostitution may obtain a license 
the ordinance also bars motel owners from renting rooms for less 
than 10 hours a provision intended to discourage prostitution 
establishments offering sexually oriented entertainment must be 
open to surveillance by authorities without search warrants 
the 5th us circuit court of appeals upheld the local law the 
appeals court said the citys campaign against urban blight crime 
and declining property values provides compelling justification 
for the regulations 
the city need only show that a criminal conviction and the 
evil to be regulated bear a substantial relationship to justify 
that aspect of the ordinance the appeals court said 
it also said that the discretion given the police chief to 
issue suspend and revoke licenses is not impermissibly broad 
the supreme court in 1986 upheld a renton wash ordinance 
restricting the location of adult theaters 
the dallas ordinance also contains strict zoning rules but the 
justices rejected a challenge to those provisions in the dallas 
law leaving them intact 
several groups have joined the dallas business owners in 
attacking the ordinance they include the american booksellers 
association the association of american publishers the national 
association of college stores and the freedom to read foundation 
citizens for decency through law and the american family 
association lined up to support the dallas ordinance 
