yugoslavias annual inflation rate hit an alltime record of 
nearly 1200 percent mostly due to sharp increases in the prices 
of vital staples and services such as electricity meat and bread 
officials in the countrys largest republic serbia have said 
they will demand markovics resignation if his program does not 
quickly curb the rampant inflation 
in a speech when he became premier in march markovic called an 
openmarket economy an ultimate achievement of mankind for which 
no alternative has yet been found 
he demanded urgent introduction of stocks and bonds private 
initiative and entrepreneurship in the yugoslav economy and an end 
to state interference in the running of businesses 
other segments of the radical marketoriented economic reforms 
underlined by markovic would include the reshaping of the banking 
system along western lines creation of a capital market and an 
end to state subsidies for lossmaking enterprises 
in addition to europes highest inflation rate yugoslavia is 
burdened by a 19 billion foreign debt a 17 percent unemployment 
rate and growing labor and ethnic unrest 
yugoslavia consists of six republics and two autonomous 
provinces each with its own government and party structure serbia 
is dominated by hardline communists 
the decentralized system of government and collective federal 
presidency were devised in 1974 constitution to prevent one 
republic from gaining sway over the others but it has resulted in 
an ineffective government by compromise 
in yugoslavia the federal government is generally responsible 
for economic policy while the collective presidency which appoints 
the premier dictates defense and foreign policy 
but the bulk of political influence in the country is 
concentrated in the communist party with power dispersed in eight 
often fractious central committees reflecting the administrative 
division of the country 
