<DOCNO> AP891004-0131 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
when it comes to holding down cholesterol when 
you eat may turn out to be as important as what you eat 
a study has found that people who nibble all day instead of 
eating three square meals have signficantly lower blood cholesterol 
levels 
the researchers said this means that cholesterol levels may be 
lowered by increasing meal frequency alone with no alteration in 
the nature or amount of the food eaten 
however they said they did not advocate putting people on the 
diet they tested which they described as an extreme model of 
nibbling 
in the study conducted at the university of toronto seven men 
ate 2500 calories a day for one twoweek period they got their 
food in three ordinarysize meals but for another two weeks they 
got the same amount of calories in 17 snacks eaten once an hour 
the nibbling diet lowered their total cholesterol levels by 9 
percent and their levels of hazardous lowdensity lipoprotein 
cholesterol or ldl by 14 percent 
nutritionists generally discourage people from eating this way 
because snackers tend to take in more calories over the course of 
the day and put on weight however some population studies suggest 
that those who eat frequently rather than gorging on one or two 
meals a day have healthier hearts 
the researchers said that what they found is consistent with 
the claim that increasing meal frequency while maintaining a 
constant caloric intake may have a role in the prevention of heart 
disease 
why this might be is unclear the researchers speculated that 
nibbling might somehow help by lowering insulin levels or prompting 
the liver to make less cholesterol 
the study directed by dr david ja jenkins was published in 
thursdays new england journal of medicine 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

