a new educational group said wednesday that 
the agricultural export policies of the united states and the 
european economic community are linked to third world development 
sometimes to the disadvantage of poor countries 
the trade and development program was recently established to 
help educate americans about the importance of farm and trade 
policy to the third world 
we all need to make these vital connections between our food 
farmers and trade policy said the programs chairman walter 
grazer of the us catholic conference education of our citizens 
is critical so they can make informed decisions and join in the 
policy process 
the nonprofit washingtonbased program is sponsored by 10 
church and farm organizations and is funded by a grant from the 
wk kellogg foundation 
educational materials including video tapes have been prepared 
for use by farm church and community groups to explore the 
linkages between trade policies and third world development 
atherton martin former agriculture minister of the commonwealth 
of dominica a caribbean island nation said measures to help us 
and european farmers such as export subsidies on grains have 
damaged the fragile economies of developing countries 
the export push was stepped up by the 1985 farm law in which 
congress created export incentives or subsidies to sell more 
us commodities overseas partly in response to similar incentives 
in europe he said 
as a result the subsidized lower prices have helped consumers 
but often have hurt farmers and slowed agricultural development in 
many nations martin said 
in a report outlining its goals and some of the challenges the 
program said no attempt will be made to reach a consensus or to 
advocate specific trade and agricultural policies however it said 
sponsors share a number of views 
agricultural trade policies should be more sensitive to the 
interests of farmers farm workers consumers and poor people 
throughout the world 
broad participation in community national and international 
decision making is crucial 
individual and community stewardship supported by sound public 
policies is critical in the care and preservation of global 
resources 
the common goals also state that maintaining us family 
farmers and vital rural communities is important to the fabric of 
the nation and that these are important resources throughout the 
world 
moderatesized farms development projects or trading 
enterprises are generally preferable to largescale undertakings 
the report said 
