rescuers in boats and helicopters 
searched the gulf of mexico today for eight people whose fishing 
boat struck a natural gas pipeline causing an explosion and 
fireball that killed three other crew members 
three of the north umberlands 14member crew were injured when 
the 160foot metalhulled boat hit the pipeline just before dark 
tuesday a halfmile offshore 
four coast guard boats and several private vessels searched 
today and the agency launched a helicopter after fog lifted coast 
guard and private helicopters with searchlights swept the area 
through the night until fog set in 
the pilot of a privatelyowned helicopter spotted the third 
victim just after noon today the coast guard recovered the body 
it was just a boom and big ball of fire went up into the air 
about 300 feet said allen willett a helicopter pilot for a 
company that ferries crews and gear to offshore drilling rigs as 
soon as i saw what it was i radioed back in and they notified the 
coast guard 
the spectacular explosion was heard by port arthur police on 
shore it made a pretty big noise sgt tk donnell said 
willett said the boat was on fire when he reached it and spotted 
three survivors and two dead 
we got three life rafts in the water and i hovered low over 
the water willett said my mechanic jumped in he got the 
one in the most distress got him inside the life raft the other 
two made it on their own 
the mechanic dennis brooks and the injured men were brought to 
shore with coast guard assistance 
the gas line was shut off early today and the fires were put out 
on the pipeline and the boat said coast guard lt scott 
larochelle coast guard spokesman don merwin said he did not know 
who owns the underwater pipeline 
mike benson spokesman for the national transportation safety 
board in washington said the agency was sending a team to 
investigate 
coast guard capt michael collan said the cameron labased 
north umberland was equipped with a fishing net but it was not 
known if the net snagged on the pipeline and broke it 
the north umberland made daily runs for menhaden a small fish 
commonly known as pogy and used for poultry feed said barney 
white spokesman for houstonbased zapada heynie corp which owns 
the boat 
three injured men were taken to baptist hospital of southeast 
texas in beaumont a 53yearold man from sulphur la was listed 
in critical condition with severe burns over 68 percent of his body 
a 28yearold cameron man was listed in serious condition with 
burns on his face and arms and a 31yearold man from lake 
charles la was in shock but listed in good condition 
names of the injured and dead were not immediately available 
