<DOCNO> AP891004-0165 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the chairman of a federal panel of experts 
said wednesday that healthy women could get by with fewer visits to 
the doctor during pregnancy but women at high risk need more and 
better prenatal care 
dr mortimer g rosen panel chairman and head of obstetrics and 
gynecology at columbia college of physicians and surgeons in new 
york said healthy women whose fetuses are at no apparent risk now 
visit a doctor about 14 times during pregnancy 
eliminating or reducing some laboratory tests and procedures 
could cut five to seven visits from this schedule according to the 
recommendations of rosens panel whose report was issued by the 
public health service this week 
the report emphasizes the need for preconception counseling to 
warn women about the dangers of smoking drinking and drug use 
before they become pregnant and recommends that this counseling be 
covered by insurance plans 
it also recommends prenatal care be available to all women 
though it did not estimate what that would cost 
more than 25 percent of women receive poor prenatal care or none 
at all rosen said resulting in a high infant mortality rate for 
the united states 
for women at low risk for problems during pregnancy some of 
the visits to their doctor dont at least obviously contribute to 
the prevention of illness and the medical health of the mother 
rosen said 
for example he said healthy women dont need to be tested for 
protein in their urine at every prenatal visit and women who have 
had a pap test within the past year dont need another just because 
they become pregnant he also said blood pressure measurements 
arent necessary during every visit and more than one pelvic exam 
during pregnancy often is not needed 
ultimately the schedule of visits should be determined by the 
patient and her physician he said adding that some women might 
want more contact with their physician and that is their right 
rosen said he expected some physicians will dispute the panels 
recommendation for healthy women but he added let the people 
who feel this is wrong test it 
the panel did not estimate the savings that could result from 
less prenatal care for healthy women or the costs for additional 
care for women with fetuses at higher risk but it expected 
considerably more public funds would be needed since many women who 
need better prenatal care live near or below the poverty line 
however providing more care before a child is born will save 
costs in the long run rosen said 
prenatal care must be accessible to all women rosen said 
frontloading of prenatal care is going to be more expensive but 
by improving the outcome youll have fewer babies in intensive 
care and they will become more productive members of society 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

