<TEXT>
cancer patients who lose hope when standard 
treatments fail are fighting to force insurance companies to pay 
for drugs and procedures that the insurers call experimental and 
beyond their coverage 
the companies argue that they should not pay for unproven 
treatments ordered by researchers investigating new cures 
the issue has brought together doctors insurers lawyers and 
judges to determine who gets what kind of care for potentially 
fatal diseases 
the dilemma took on a human face wednesday when a federal judge 
here heard arguments on whether to force a health maintenance 
organization to pay for a 75000to125000 bone marrow 
transplant for a 22yearold truck driver with testicular cancer 
doctors said dean weeks of bernardsville needed the transplant 
immediately minutes before testimony was to begin memorial 
sloankettering cancer institute agreed to pay for the treatment 
out of charitable funds 
us district judge john bissell said he would hold a hearing on 
whether the hmo healthways systems inc of woodcliff lake should 
be required to reimburse sloankettering 
weeks was diagnosed a year ago and chemotherapy failed to stem 
the cancer 
hopefully ill get cured said weeks who sat next to his 
fiancee during the hearing i dont know what to say im just 
glad to have the treatment 
his lawyer kevin kovacs said forcing the hospital to pay for 
weeks could deny a future uninsured patient the chance for 
treatment 
healthways attorney jeffrey w pagano argued that forcing the 
hmo to fund experimental treatments could harm the quality of basic 
care for all its members kovacs said the hmo never defined 
experimental 
weeks needs an autologous bone marrow transplant in which his 
blood cellproducing bone marrow would be temporarily removed so 
high levels of chemotherapy can be applied that otherwise could 
kill the bone marrow 
the procedure is considered nonexperimental for certain kinds 
of cancers but not others including testicular cancer it is used 
when standard treatment fails 
in a parallel case in the same courthouse last spring us 
district judge dickinson r debevoise forced prudential insurance 
co and another firm to pay for the procedure for nicholae dosza 
60 of jefferson township 
some companies have also balked at paying for interleuken and 
lak or killer cell therapies which stimulate the bodys own 
response to cancer said john wingard an associate professor of 
oncology at johns hopkins university who treated dosza 
the problem is the same for aids treatment in which insurers 
lag behind federal approvals for new therapies said tom stoddard 
executive director of the lambda legal defense and education fund 
the insurance industrys cautious approach to new treatments is 
not based on monetary concerns argued susan pohli a prudential 
insurance co spokeswoman 
the issue isnt money the issue is safety she said 
insurers are justified in having a say in whether a treatment is 
effective or properly documented said jude payne a senior policy 
analyst for the health insurance association of america 
a key problem arises when doctors vary drug dosages or even 
uses beyond uses approved by insurance companies 
it really boils down to what is standard medical practice and 
what can be documented as effective said ms payne i think 
sometimes theres a little bit of tension there 
the insurers also argue that drugmakers seeking profits and 
researchers needing data should help pay for experimental 
treatments 
it may very well be that in lifethreatening situations where 
theres no alternative an exception should be made for insurers 
to foot the bill even if a therapy is still being investigated 
said ms payne 
