the soviet union has bought 100000 metric 
tons of soybean meal and an additional 200000 tons of corn for 
delivery in 198990 under a longterm supply agreement the 
agriculture department said wednesday 
the meal and corn were on top of an order for 2 million tons of 
corn announced tuesday the seventh year of the longterm agreement 
between the two countries began oct 1 
us grain sales to moscow in 198889 the sixth year of the 
agreement were a record of more than 217 million tons including 
more than 163 million tons of corn and nearly 54 million tons of 
wheat 
in addition the 198889 sales included 442500 tons of 
soybeans 135 million tons of soybean meal and 102 million tons 
of grain sorghums 
a metric ton is about 2205 pounds and is equal to 394 bushels 
of corn or 367 bushels of wheat or soybeans the 200000 tons of 
corn would be about 788 million bushels 
the new sales were made by unidentified private exporting 
companies which are required to report large sales to the 
department no selling prices or further details were released 
corn prices have been averaging about 222 per bushel at the 
farm according to usdas fiveday average meaning that the latest 
sale could have a farm value of around 175 million 
soybean meal has been selling at wholesale in illinois at an 
equivalent of around 220 per metric ton that would make the 
latest soviet purchase worth around 22 million at the us plant 
