cypriot president george vassiliou conferred 
with president bush on wednesday and said he is willing to 
demilitarize cyprus if turkey withdraws its troops from the island 
vassiliou met in the oval office with bush secretary of state 
james a baker iii national security adviser brent scowcroft and 
bushs special cyprus negotiator nelson ledsky 
white house press secretary marlin fitzwater said afterwards 
that bush reaffirmed us support for un efforts to negotiate a 
solution to the cyprus problem bush expressed his hope that the 
talks will be resumed at the earliest possible date fitzwater 
said 
vassiliou speaking with reporters on the white house driveway 
called it an extremely good meeting im extremely 
satisfied 
he said bush made it quite clear that he does not consider 
the status quo as a solution 
turkey invaded cyprus in 1974 and in 1983 turkish cypriots 
declared a breakaway republic in their third of the eastern 
mediterranean island turkey still has 30000 troops on the island 
where un peacekeeping forces help keep the peace between the 
majority greek cypriots and the turkish minority 
vassiliou said his government has been building up its military 
for defensive purposes but he insisted its army of 10000 to 
12000 conscripts is no match for the turkish forces 
he repeated a challenge first delivered earlier in the day in a 
speech to the un general assembly in new york 
i challenge the turkish government if theyre really worried 
about our building up our defenses lets demilitarize we are 
ready to do that any moment he said 
lets start they withdraw their armies we dismantle our army 
and also give away all our guns and lets have cyprus 
demilitarized under any kind of guarantees 
vassiliou called upon leaders of turkey and the turkish cypriots 
to stop making difficulties and sit down and talk 
i would like to give this message to the turkish people its 
an anachronism to have the cyprus issue open it helps nobody it 
causes pain to all of us and it costs a lot of money that we could 
use much better for the benefit of our people 
cyprus with its problems would be a good friend of turkey 
would be a place where turkish cypriots and greek cypriots would 
feel happy and will contriute significantly to peace in the 
region he said 
he said the impoverished turkish cypriot community had the most 
to gain from a solution 
vassiliou gave bush a gift of an ancient vase from cyprus 
dating to 600 bc 
