<TEXT>
eighteen east germans who occupied the us 
embassy in an effort to flee to the west left the compound late 
wednesday with assurances their government will look favorably on 
their emigration requests diplomats said 
earlier in the day east german police cordoned off the embassy 
in east berlin and scuffled with about 50 other refugees also 
hoping to gain sanctuary there 
elsewhere thousands of other east germans lined railroad tracks 
with packed bags and children in tow hoping to jump aboard trains 
carrying their countrymen to the west from prague czechoslovakia 
witnesses said the trains were to pass through east germany on 
their way to hof west germany 
east germany reluctantly agreed to allow the exodus the second 
in the last four days after thousands of its citizens flooded 
embassies in prague and warsaw poland 
wednesdays scuffle in east berlin came a day after the 18 east 
germans moved into the embassy and refused to leave until they were 
given permission to emigrate from their communist homeland 
according to a statement from the us embassy those 18 agreed 
to leave the mission wednesday night and went home east german 
officials have promised to examine with goodwill their 
emigration applications the statement said 
western diplomats in east berlin said they assume the group will 
soon be permitted to leave for west germany though it was not 
clear if east german authorities explicitly made such a promise 
after agreeing to the latest rail exodus the hardline east 
berlin government on tuesday closed its border with czechoslovakia 
that is the only country where east germans could freely travel 
without government permission 
that closure and the sanctioned exodus from prague has triggered 
a flood of other east germans desperately trying to take part in 
the mass transfer 
witnesses said about 100 east german police scuffled with about 
50 wouldbe emigres in front of the us embassy preventing their 
entry there were no reports of injuries 
western reporters saw at least 12 people taken away in police 
vans among them a young mother and three wailing children 
the embassy was circled by police and passersby were checked 
for documents and told to leave the area on the corner of the 
nearby central thoroughfare unter den linden scores of onlookers 
gathered to watch 
us embassy spokesman jerry verner said the 18 east germans 
10 adults and eight children were holed up in the embassy since 
late tuesday 
before leaving the refugees were staying in a cramped room just 
off the embassy entrance lobby they were mostly couples in their 
20s and many had small children and babies in strollers and baskets 
this is our last hope one refugee had said were not 
going to budge until we know well be able to leave 
diplomatic sources also speaking on condition of anonymity 
said four east german refugees fled to the west german diplomatic 
mission in east berlin 
in washington white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said of 
the refugee influx were talking to the east germans about it 
and trying to get them to help resolve the problem through their 
immigration policies 
hungarian and west german media reported that thousands more had 
crowded other spots along the route the trains are taking through 
east germany many had their belongings packed and were hoping to 
jump on the trains as many did during last weekends exodus 
in dresden witnesses said police used truncheons to clear about 
5000 east germans from the citys central station who gathered 
since tuesday in hopes of climbing on the westernbound trains 
after being forced out of the station witnesses said more then 
5000 people stretched in a line along the tracks the crowd 
dispersed by early wednesday after learning the trains from prague 
were delayed 
during last weekends exodus of about 7000 east germans 
several managed to board a train in dresden as it passed 
police officials in the west german border town of hof where 
the refugees were to arrive said about 1000 young east germans 
were waiting along the tracks near plauen an east german town near 
the czechoslovak border 
the embarassing exodus comes as east german plans a weekend 
celebration of its 40th anniversary to be attended by soviet 
leader mikhail s gorbachev 
