<TEXT>
a blood bank plans to start reporting the 
names of aids carriers to health authorities who in turn will try 
to trace the patients sexual contacts officials said 
we dont want people with aids or people at high risk for aids 
donating blood said ken wiebeck spokesman for the southwest 
florida blood bank its not right its not safe the safety of 
the public is of primary importance 
also the blood bank wants to discourage people from using 
donations as a way to get a free confidential aids test 
one of our fears is that people may be donating blood to get a 
confidential test for aids said dr paul schmidt director of 
the blood bank and a recent past president of the american 
association of blood banks 
a spokesman for aids patients advised caution in reporting names 
passing along names would scare people said chuck kuehn 
executive director of the tampa aids network they would have 
achieved their purpose but i dont agree with their tactics 
the tampa blood bank is considered among the most aggressive in 
the country in trying to prevent aids carriers from donating blood 
in march 1988 the bank became one of two in the united states to 
start interviewing donors to identify highrisk applicants a san 
bernardino calif blood bank was the other 
donors will be told of the policy and asked to sign a form 
acknowledging they were so advised if tests show young donors 17 
or 18 carry the human immunodeficiency virus or hiv which causes 
acquired immune deficiency syndrome the blood bank will notify 
their parents or guardian 
dr don kwalick director of the hillsborough county health 
department said his employees intend to follow the same procedures 
they use in tracing contacts of patients with other sexually 
transmitted diseases names from the blood bank would be used as 
one source of information in tracing contacts 
he said recently passed laws let the department include aids 
patients in the tracing but that state health and rehabilitative 
services officials have to give their permission 
the health department offers anonymous and confidential aids 
testing 
the blood bank has been identifying between one and two donors 
that test positive for the aids virus for every 10000 units of 
blood donated that is about what would be expected nationally 
wiebeck said 
in the interview process potential donors are asked a series of 
questions instead of simply being asked to complete a form saying 
they do not fall into highrisk categories 
the tampa data showed 62 donors out of the approximately 36000 
seen since the questioning began were deferred because they 
gave a positive response to a question 
the questions include 
have you had sexual contact with prostitutes in the past six 
months 
have you had clinical or laboratory evidence of aids infection 
or had sexual contact with someone who has 
have you engaged in male homosexual activity or had sexual 
contact with someone who had 
two additional questions ask about intravenous drug use and 
whether the donor has immigrated from haiti or west or central 
africa since 1977 or had sexual contact with an immigrant from 
those regions 
</TEXT>
