<TEXT>
a state superintendent took control of 
jersey citys faltering public schools wednesday completing a 
fiveyear legal struggle that ended in the nations largest state 
takeover of an urban school district 
jersey city students have been subjected to educational child 
abuse said gov thomas h kean now the community can put 
politics and patronage aside and get on with the business of 
learning 
the state had cited political intrusion in hiring practices 
poor test scores failure to provide a safe clean environment for 
students violations of bidding laws failure to provide for 
handicapped children and unauthorized use of state funds as some of 
the reasons for the takeover 
on wednesday the state board of education in jamesburg gave 
final approval to the takeover and formally appointed elena j 
scambio to a threeyear term as superintendent of the school 
district 
ms scambios first act was to abolish the jobs of seven top 
administrators in the district including that of school 
superintendent franklin williams the state boards action also 
officially disbanded the jersey city board of education 
a new board is expected to be appointed by state education 
commissioner saul cooperman by december 
ms scambio a former essex county school superintendent who has 
been preparing for the transition since august promised to 
unravel the quagmire that exists in jersey city and make the 
city a national model of urban education 
under new jerseys takeover law the state has five years to 
make improvements national education groups say they will closely 
monitor the progress of the takeover 
the move gives the state extraordinary powers in jersey city 
the states second largest district with 28000 students 
ms scambio said other immediate changes may include trimming 
from 100 to 150 staff positions streamlined management physical 
improvements to schools and better community relations 
the jersey city school system has a staff of 3322 and a budget 
for the current year of about 180 million enrollment is 44 
percent black 34 percent hispanic and 13 percent white 
the boards decision was expected and ends a bitter legal battle 
by the state to take over the schools a process strongly pushed by 
kean who has billed himself as the education governor 
state board vice president robert a woodruff reading a 
resolution said the districts problems were deeprooted and 
endemic the jersey city board of education totally failed to meet 
its obligations 
this summer administrative law judge kenneth springer agreed 
with the argument of state officials in his decision to grant the 
state power to take over the district 
springer noted that some textbooks used in jersey city 
classrooms are more than 30 years old 
jersey city officials bitterly fought the takeover effort 
saying the problems were caused by a prior administration and that 
the state trumped up its case against the district 
williams who was relieved as school superintendent but can 
still teach in the district released a statement wednesday 
criticizing the takeover effort 
in a society that offers little enough to bolster the 
selfconfidence of urban children the campaign to take over the 
jersey city schools has only further lowered the selfimage of our 
students williams said 
williams said test scores have climbed in recent years and one 
of the districts high schools was one of only five in the state 
with a 100 percent passing rate on the high school proficiency test 
local officials had at first sought to rally public opinion 
against the intervention but found little political support former 
mayor anthony cuccio who opposed the takeover lost his seat in 
may to gerald mccann who said he would not oppose the move 
it should have happened much sooner i think said samir 
skular 31 a 31yearold city resident with two daughters in the 
public schools it was just politicians trying to protect their 
jobs and not thinking about kids 
jean mcdonald a researcher for the national governors 
association said kentucky south carolina texas and new mexico 
have laws allowing state takeovers of failing school districts 
in kentucky the state school board has taken limited control of 
three county districts under an academic bankruptcy law enacted 
by the general assembly in 1988 
</TEXT>
