rj reynolds tobacco co has settled a 
federal false advertising claim by agreeing not to misrepresent 
in future advertisements the results of a study that linked 
smoking and heart disease 
the federal trade commission was divided 31 over accepting the 
settlement which was termed conspicuously weak by the 
dissenter commissioner mary l azcuenaga 
she said the acceptance demonstrates a modicum of interest at 
most in important issues related to smoking and health and 
indicates a double standard for deceptive advertising and lenient 
treatment for reynolds 
commissioner andrew j strenio jr defended the agreement 
calling it both justified and commensurately strong he said it 
provides appropriate disincentives against recurrence of the 
allegedly unfair and deceptive claims 
in a statement the tobacco firm said tuesday it remains 
convinced its advertising message constituted an exercise of free 
speech but that it felt there was no purpose in continuing its 
fight with the ftc 
we have decided therefore to accept a settlement that puts the 
matter behind the company rj reynolds said 
the ftc complained that a reynolds advertisement made false and 
misleading claims about a longterm study funded by the national 
institutes of health 
reynolds advertisement falsely claimed that the study 
provided scientific evidence that smoking is not as hazardous as 
the public has been led to believe the ftc complaint said also 
said the ftc the ad falsely maintained that the study tends to 
refute the theory that smoking causes heart disease 
the consent agreement is not an admission that the law was 
violated and it can become final after more commission debate 
after a 60day comment period by the public 
commission chairman janet d steiger did not vote on the order 
