the senate finance committee early wednesday 
defeated a proposed cut in the capitalgains tax and on a tie vote 
approved a substitute savingincentive plan that would allow all 
workers to have taxdeductible individual retirement accounts 
nearing final action on a bill whose main purpose is to cut the 
federal deficit by about 8 billion in the fiscal year that began 
sunday the committee formally approved a 63 percent increase in 
the amount older americans may earn without losing any of their 
social security benefits 
the 1billionayear change would benefit only the most 
affluent 10 percent of social security beneficiaries 
on a 1010 vote nearly along party lines the committee retained 
a proposal in the bill by chairman lloyd bentsen dtexas to 
liberalize iras the same vote rejected a cut in capitalgains tax 
offered by sen bob packwood rore along lines recommended by 
president bush only sen david boren dokla broke party ranks 
siding with the gop proposal 
packwoods amendment also included some ira provisions allowing 
workers to contribute to an account without any immediate tax 
deduction but exempting interest from ever being taxed 
bentsen said that would simply shift the costs of iras to a 
future generation he portrayed his own plan as superior to 
packwoods and to a different capitalgains reduction approved by 
the house 
republicans made clear they will renew the capitalgains fight 
on the senate floor as early as this week 
most of the spending cuts in the bill would affect medicare 
reimbursements to hospitals and doctors one provision would save 
money by overhauling the fee schedule for reimbursing doctors 
basing fees on the time training and skill required to provide a 
particular service 
also added to the bill over objections of the bush 
administration was a provision removing the social security 
administration from the department of health and human services and 
creating it as an indepenent agency a similar change is awaiting 
final action in the house 
the change in the social security earnings limitation which the 
panel had tentatively approved monday would benefit only the most 
affluent retirees between ages 65 and 69 those who earn more than 
8880 a year in retirement that would be about one of every 10 
social security beneficiaries in that age group 
the committee agreed without discussion or dissent to boost the 
limit to 11700 next year and then to 14520 on the next 5000 
of earnings to a total of 19520 the social security recipient 
would give up 1 in benefits for each 4 earned 
once earnings pass 19520 the penalty would be 1 for each 3 
earned above the limit 
present law requires a retiree between the ages of 65 and 69 to 
give up 1 in social security pension for each 2 earned above the 
8880 earnings limit the penalty is scheduled to drop next year 
to 1 for each 3 earned above the limit 
a separate 6480 limit affecting beneficiaries under age 65 
would not be changed by the committees proposal those 70 or older 
could continue to earn an unlimited amount without penalty 
the house has agreed to a more modest increase in the 6569 
earnings limit to 9720 next year and 10440 in 1991 
the finance committee voted to pay for the increase by requiring 
that deferred compensation such as earnings set aside in a 401k 
retirement plan be included in the formula that determines 
average total wages for social security purposes 
the shortrun effect is to increase the amount of wages subject 
to social security taxes in the long run the change would cost 
the government more than it brings in by forcing up social 
security benefits 
the committee added to the bill a requirement that starting in 
1995 the government each year send a statement of social security 
benefits earned sto every person 60 and older starting in 1999 
statements would have to be mailed to every worker 
