challenging lin to either put up or shut up in new york 
the most immediate question for lin officials would be whether 
they wanted to borrow 19 billion to buy out metro one taking on 
the additional debt could make lin less attractive in its own 
efforts to merge with bellsouth corp in a 5050 partnership 
analysts said 
in june mccaw offered to buy lin for 585 billion lin 
rejected that offer but mccaw persisted and dropped its offer 
from 127 per share to 110 per share after a court decision in 
july against lin which had claimed it owned key cellular franchise 
rights in philadelphia and new york ciy 
the 110ashare offer for approximately 53 million lin shares 
has been extended to oct 13 despite lins september announcement 
that it intended to merge with bellsouth 
mccaw lins largest shareholder with a 10 percent stake has 
been tendered more than 8 million lin shares said tom campo at 
adams amp rinehart inc a new york public relations agency 
representing mccaw 
the contel agreement would provide mccaw about 13 billion in 
cash or about 205 a pop an industry yardstick obtained by 
multiplying a market area population by the percentage ownership of 
cellular systems serving the market 
each market is allowed two cellular franchises one for the 
local telephone company and one for an independent operation like 
mccaw 
the contel agreement which is subject to closing price 
adjustments would make the contel corp subsidiary the nations 
seventhlargest cellular phone company gaining controlling 
cellular interests in 13 southeastern markets including louisville 
and lexington ky nashville memphis knoxville johnson city 
chattanooga and clarksville tenn and birmingham tuscaloosa 
florence anniston and gadsden ala 
the metromedia deal covers about 68 million pops and works out 
to about 275 a pop the contel deal is about 61 million pops 
atlantabased contel currently has about 144 million pops 
these are two more steps toward achieving our longstanding 
strategic objective of creating a national cellular network that 
will give american consumers an independent alternative to 
traditional providers of telephone service mccaw chairman craig 
o mccaw said 
he described contel as a fellow independent with whom we have 
had a long and mutually beneficial relationship 
mccaw based in this seattle suburb operates in 127 areas with 
a total of 50 million pops in 26 states including major regional 
systems along the west coast and in the rocky mountains northeast 
florida and texas 
