<TEXT>
unisys corp said it hopes to see savings 
in the fourth quarter from a restructuring plan that will reduce 
the work force by 8000 and annual costs by more than 400 million 
the costcutting moves originally announced aug 18 and begun 
this week are designed to counter weak domestic demand for 
computers and defense electronics products and stiffer worldwide 
competition 
unisys said tuesday it plans to cut roughly 1000 more jobs than 
originally expected when it first announced the restructuring 
the austerity measures involve laying off 6300 people and 
eliminating 1700 positions through attrition and early retirement 
that will reduce the work force by nearly 10 percent to about 
80000 worldwide the company said 
w michael blumenthal unisys chairman and chief executive 
officer said the restructuring plan was the result of months of 
planning 
the actions being announced today will reduce our costs in 
1990 significantly and along with other planned improvements this 
will lead to a substantial lowering of our breakeven point he 
said tuesday 
by simplifying our organizational structure and shortening 
lines of communication we will be better able to meet our 
customers needs 
blumenthal said the cost of restructuring would be announced 
later this month with the thirdquarter financial results the 
company said it expects to take a substantial charge in the third 
quarter 
unisys has been losing ground in the mainframe and minicomputer 
markets lately in addition its big defense business has lagged 
partly due to slowing growth in the us defense budget and also 
because of a threemonth suspension in its dealings with the 
government tied to the companys involvement in the pentagon 
procurement scandal 
unisys is cutting jobs throughout the company including on the 
corporate level according to unisys spokesman j peter hynes 
this week the company plans to eliminate 3200 jobs at 250 
sites in the united states an additional 1200 jobs outside the 
united states will be cut by the first quarter of 1990 unisys the 
nations no 3 computer company will continue cutting 1900 jobs 
later this year and into 1990 
in addition to layoffs the plan involves eliminating overhead 
and consolidating administrative and technical support functions 
reducing manufacturing overseas and increasing the move toward 
inhouse production of the companys major microprocessor lines 
the company said it expects the program to lower the companys 
breakeven point by more than 15 billion meaning that if it were 
to break even on roughly 10 billion of sales it expects to post 
for this year it would be able to break even on 85 billion of 
sales in 1990 
last quarter the company reported a 67 percent decrease in 
earnings blaming a drop in inventory pricing pressure from 
competitors and a temporary suspension of pentagon work 
hynes said the companys consolidation plans include 
transferring the manufacture of computer mainframes from tredyffrin 
to clear lake iowa by mid1990 unisys will close its st 
laurent canada plant in 1990 and shift its engineering support to 
rancho bernardo calif 
most of the manufacturing at the unisys peripherals group in 
santa clara calif hardest hit with 350 job cuts will be 
consolidated into other facilities 
in addition hynes said unisys is implementing a new plan to 
strengthen its approach to selected markets and to reallocate 
support services the original plan was adopted in 1986 when sperry 
corp and burroughs corp merged 
</TEXT>
