the agriculture department says the soviet 
union has bought 2 million metric tons of us corn the first for 
delivery in 198990 under a longterm supply agreement 
rumors had been circulating in the grain trade that the soviets 
were in the market for a large order of us corn the seventh year 
of the longterm agreement between the two countries began oct 1 
officials said us grain sales to moscow in 198889 the sixth 
year of the agreement were a record of more than 217 million tons 
including more than 163 million tons of corn and nearly 54 
million tons of wheat 
in addition 198889 sales included 442500 tons of soybeans 
135 million tons of soybean meal and 102 million tons of grain 
sorghums 
a metric ton is about 2205 pounds and is equal to 394 bushels 
of corn or 367 bushels of wheat or soybeans the 2 million tons of 
corn would be about 788 million bushels 
the sales were made by unidentified private exporting companies 
which are required by law to report large sales to the department 
no selling prices or further details were released 
arthur k homann of the departments foreign agricultural 
service said it was the soviet unions largest single order of us 
corn in at least three years although there were several orders of 
more than 1 million each last year 
corn prices have been averaging about 222 per bushel at the 
farm level according to usdas fiveday average meaning that the 
latest sale could have a farm value of about 175 million 
the agreement was extended last year until dec 31 1990 
meanwhile the united states and the soviet union are preparing to 
begin preliminary talks in moscow on dec 4 for a new longterm 
agreement 
under the current agreement the soviets are committed to buy at 
least 9 million tons of grain annually including a minimum of 4 
million tons each of wheat and corn and 1 million tons that can be 
wheat corn soybeans and soybean meal or any combination of those 
commodities 
the pact also allows moscow to buy up to 3 million tons of 
additional wheat and corn annually without further discussions if 
more than 12 million tons are wanted however the united states 
must be consulted 
