<TEXT>
a spraypainted tin sign over aldo ranieris idle pumps hangs as 
an epitaph to a oncethriving business no gas 
ranieri is one of more than 20000 independent service station 
owners nationwide likely to go out of business because of new 
environmental safety rules concerning underground storage tanks 
the potential closures represent almost a fifth of all us 
gasoline retail outlets threatening to significantly narrow 
competition and raise prices particularly in rural areas 
federal officials say the rules are aimed at protecting the 
environment from underground leaks that could contaminate water 
supplies 
thats no consolation to people like ranieri who cannot afford 
the enormous cost of replacing and insuring his tanks help 
thats what i need help ranieri says 
after 25 years of pumping gasoline at the same location in an 
affluent westchester county suburb of new york ranieri says state 
officials forced him to stop selling gasoline four months ago when 
he refused to have his tanks tested at a cost of several thousand 
dollars 
he has since laid off all but two employees who continue to 
repair cars in the garage 
the federal regulations require service station owners to 
replace or upgrade underground tanks by 1998 before then they must 
test their tanks install leak detection devices and prove through 
pollution liability insurance or other means that they can pay 
damages if theres a leak 
oct 26 is the deadline for owners of between 100 and 999 tanks 
to have 1 million in insurance coverage to pay for possible leaks 
those who opt not to take the 1 million insurance generally 
must be able to show they have a minimum net worth of 10 million 
to cover the cost of cleaning a leak 
with annual premiums more than doubling from an average of 
25356 in 1986 to 66064 in 1989 industry officials say many 
station owners will not be able to comply by the deadline 
fiftyfive percent of the people who should have insurance by 
oct 26 wont and the situation is getting worse says phillip r 
chisholm executive vice president of the petroleum marketers 
association of america 
a joint survey by three trade associations representing us 
gasoline marketers the petroleum marketers the national 
association of convenience stores and the society of independent 
gasoline marketers found that about 37000 retailers with 100000 
tanks will likely miss the october deadline 
smaller owners like ranieri who own only a few tanks have 
until october 1990 to get coverage but they face a december 
deadline for testing tanks and installing leak detectors 
ranieri says he has asked texaco inc for help since he sells 
the companys brand under a franchise but has been turned down 
hes now seeking a buyer 
texaco concedes it has no program to help independent tank 
owners 
its their responsibility said texaco spokesman gary 
taylor he said texaco is considering assisting wholesalers with 
insurance costs 
the petroleum marketers association estimates that at least 
26250 of the nations 150000 gasoline stations could close over 
the next few years as a result of the environmental protection 
agency rules 
ranieri says his tanks are at least 30 years old and need 
replacing he estimates the cost could exceed 200000 including 
compliance with state regulations that require installation of 
antivapor safety nozzles 
im a little guy for me to survive i have to replace the 
tanks i dont have the money he says 
across the street at a mobil station business has picked up 
since ranieris pumps closed one recent weekday morning a stream 
of cars pulled in and out almost nonstop the few unwary motorists 
who drove into ranieris texaco glimpsed the sign then wheeled over 
to the mobil pumps 
theyre busy all the time ranieri says im too small to 
fight i cant fight the big guys 
owners of 1000 or more tanks such as mobil corp which 
operates the mobil station had to be in compliance by last 
january most large oil companies already are self insured 
since the rules went into effect last december all tank owners 
are required to start testing the estimated 2 million underground 
oil and gasoline tanks nationwide up to half are believed to 
contain hazardous contaminants such as lead 
nobody is questioning the need for this says ron brand 
director of epas underground storage tank program the issue is 
who pays not whether we need it 
older storage tanks are made of carbon steel which corrodes 
and have typical design lives of 1520 years products stored in 
leaky or corroding tanks seep into water and underground wells 
tanks installed since 1985 had to be constructed of protected 
steel fiberglass or a sturdy composite with noncorroding pipes 
jim mccormick director of epas policy and standards division 
for underground storage tanks says that leak damage often is 
underestimated 
theyre not love canals theyre much smaller but there are 
lots more of them mccormick says 
up to 30 percent of the tanks could be leaking although there 
is no reliable estimate of the extent of environmental harm 
mccormick says 
states such as california and florida which started testing 
earlier than others have found evidence of widespread leaks that 
range in size from trickles to thousands of gallons 
epa officials say they are trying to ease the burden of the new 
regulations by phasing in the rules and giving special 
consideration to problem cases 
one provision for example enables epa commissioner william k 
reilly to suspend enforcement of the insurance deadline for six 
months if coverage is not available brand says 
but tank owners should not depend on the provision brand says 
because we dont have evidence that its not available 
the petroleum marketers group has asked the epa to suspend the 
compliance date for one year arguing that many insurance companies 
remain reluctant to provide coverage before tanks are upgraded 
other insurers require 100000 deductibles chisholm says 
industry sources say that some banks also are reluctant to lend 
money for tank upgrades because they consider it a highrisk loan 
so many tank owners are in a catch 22 situation 
while some states are coming to the rescue by establishing trust 
funds to help owners upgrade tanks and cover the major portion of 
spills only a few have been approved by the epa so far 
the way i see it im out of business says ranieri 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

