<TEXT>
two former researchers at a johnson amp 
johnson subsidiary have charged the company withheld vital 
information about a painkiller that was linked to severe reactions 
and at least nine deaths before it was pulled from the market in 
1983 
in a lawsuit filed in state superior court in new brunswick the 
former mcneil pharmaceutical division researchers allege johnson amp 
johnson engaged in a corporate conspiracy to get drugs on the 
market even if they were medically inadequate and to maximize 
sales of the same regardless of consequences 
dr edward lemanowicz mcneils former assistant director of 
regulatory affairs and dr james dale former assistant director 
of medical research also contend they were forced out of mcneil 
for refusing to take part in the alleged coverup 
zomax a prescription painkiller developed in the 1970s was 
pulled from the market in march 1983 after more than 2000 reports 
of violent reactions and at least nine deaths 
johnson amp johnson based in new brunswick issued a onepage 
statement wednesday that refuted the accusations 
zomax was voluntarily withdrawn from the market in 1983 
because of an increase in reports of allergic reactions it said 
there is no basis for their charge that johnson amp johnson and 
mcneil pharmaceutical falsified or delayed reporting any data about 
zomax or any other drug the statement said both of these 
former employees were treated with respect and consideration by 
mcneil and neither was asked to say or do anything inconsistent 
with the highest professional standards 
allan kanner an attorney representing the researchers said his 
clients sued because practices that allowed zomax to be approved by 
the food and drug administration and mass marketed despite 
potentially deadly side effects were never reformed 
this is not a suit solely about zomax he said this goes 
to the nature of what a corporation does the reality is that the 
people who get promoted there are the people who care more about 
the result of sales than protecting the publics health 
kanner said dale a physician who objected several times during 
the drugs development and the fda approval process was concerned 
that testing was insufficient that evidence of possible longterm 
kidney damage was discounted by the company and that warning labels 
for prescribing doctors were insufficient 
once on the market the suit alleges mcneil mishandled and 
understated telephone reports of adverse reactions that were made 
to the drug maker 
kanner said dale took several calls about patients who 
reportedly died after taking zomax 
he said dales superiors at johnson amp johnson rewrote the 
reports to hide the severity of the reported reactions and then 
destroyed dales source notes the reports were then sent to the 
fda 
kanner said neither of his clients was fired but instead were 
sent into a kind of corporate siberia he said the doctors were 
seeking compensation for lost wages lost tenure and possible 
punitive damages 
